text: ELIZA is a computer program designed to simulate natural language conversations with a user.
ELIZA was developed at MIT using the MAC time-sharing system and written in MAD-SLIP language.
ELIZA operates by using decomposition rules, triggered by key words in the user's input, to generate responses.
The goal of ELIZA is to provide a tool for the study of natural language communication between humans and computers.
Large language models (LLMs) can be used to ground language in robotic affordances, enabling embodied agents to follow high-level instructions and complete complex tasks.

SayCan, a method for grounding LLMs in robotic affordances, extracts knowledge from an LLM and combines it with value functions that provide information about the environment to predict whether a given skill can be executed from a given state.

SayCan was evaluated on 101 real-world robotic tasks in a kitchen environment, where it was able to complete long-horizon, abstract instructions and achieved a success rate of 84% for planning and 74% for execution.
SayCan's performance improves with larger and more powerful LLMs, demonstrating a potential future for collaborative improvements in the fields of language processing and robotics.
SayCan is able to incorporate new skills and handle complex reasoning tasks, including those involving negation, through the use of chain-of-thought prompting.
SayCan is able to handle multilingual queries with minimal loss in performance, demonstrating its ability to generalize to new languages.
Large Language Models (LLMs) can be used for embodied reasoning, which requires an agent to understand semantic aspects of the world.
Inner Monologue investigates how LLMs can reason over sources of feedback through natural language without additional training.
Inner Monologue leverages environment feedback to form an inner monologue that allows for rich processing and planning in robotic control scenarios.
Inner Monologue utilizes three types of feedback including success detection, scene description, and human interaction.
Closed-loop language feedback significantly improves high-level instruction completion in simulated and real-world robotic scenarios.
